INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9d79692c-f486-4705-b9c6-9e3f2b210ebb',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$XGBoost Regularization — Taming Overfitting with the Right Knobs$escape$,
  $escape$XGBoost has no dropout or batch normalization — those are neural network concepts. Its regularization toolkit is tree-specific and highly effective when tuned correctly.

`reg_lambda` (L2, default=1) penalizes large leaf weights, smoothing predictions. `reg_alpha` (L1, default=0) drives leaf weights toward zero, useful when many features are irrelevant. Raise `reg_lambda` first before touching tree depth.

Subsampling acts like dropout: `subsample` (rows) and `colsample_bytree` / `colsample_bylevel` / `colsample_bynode` (features) inject stochasticity per tree, level, or split respectively. Values in the 0.6–0.9 range consistently reduce variance without sacrificing too much bias.

`min_child_weight` controls the minimum Hessian sum in a leaf — higher values prevent splits on noisy samples. `gamma` sets the minimum loss reduction required to make a split, acting as a hard pruning gate.

Early stopping via `early_stopping_rounds` is your last line of defense: it halts training when eval metric stops improving, preventing the model from memorizing training noise.$escape$,
  $escape$import xgboost as xgb
from sklearn.datasets import make_classification
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

X, y = make_classification(n_samples=10000, n_features=50, random_state=42)
X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2)

model = xgb.XGBClassifier(
    n_estimators=1000,
    learning_rate=0.05,
    max_depth=4,
    reg_lambda=2.0,        # L2 — primary regularizer
    reg_alpha=0.1,         # L1 — sparse features
    subsample=0.8,         # row sampling per tree
    colsample_bytree=0.7,  # feature sampling per tree
    min_child_weight=5,    # min Hessian per leaf
    gamma=0.2,             # min gain to split
    early_stopping_rounds=50,
    eval_metric="logloss"
)
model.fit(X_train, y_train, eval_set=[(X_val, y_val)], verbose=False)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
