INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ddf30371-336c-40db-ad76-8984bc799c8e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$XGBoost Model Serialization — Choosing the Right Format for Your Pipeline$escape$,
  $escape$XGBoost offers three serialization formats, each with distinct trade-offs. The native binary format (`model.save_model('model.ubj')` using UBJ, or `.json`) is the recommended default — it preserves the full booster state including feature names, enabling cross-language loading (Python, R, C++, Java). Avoid the deprecated pickle approach: it ties you to a specific XGBoost version and Python runtime, breaking portability.

For training checkpoints on large datasets, use `callbacks=[xgb.callback.TrainingCheckpoint(directory='ckpts/', iterations=50)]` inside `xgb.train()`. This saves intermediate boosters every 50 rounds so a crash doesn't cost you hours of compute. Resume by loading the checkpoint with `xgb.Booster()` and passing it as `xgb_model` to the next `xgb.train()` call.

JSON format is human-readable and diff-friendly — useful in MLOps pipelines where you need to audit or version tree structures in Git. UBJ (Universal Binary JSON) is faster to read/write and smaller on disk; prefer it for production inference. Always verify round-trip fidelity with `np.testing.assert_array_almost_equal(bst.predict(dmat), loaded_bst.predict(dmat))`.$escape$,
  $escape$import xgboost as xgb
import numpy as np

# Train with checkpointing every 50 rounds
params = {"objective": "binary:logistic", "max_depth": 6, "eta": 0.1}
cbs = [xgb.callback.TrainingCheckpoint(directory="ckpts/", iterations=50)]
bst = xgb.train(params, dtrain, num_boost_round=300, callbacks=cbs)

# Save in UBJ (production) or JSON (auditable)
bst.save_model("model.ubj")   # compact, fast
bst.save_model("model.json")  # human-readable, VCS-friendly

# Load and verify round-trip
loaded = xgb.Booster()
loaded.load_model("model.ubj")
np.testing.assert_array_almost_equal(bst.predict(dtest), loaded.predict(dtest))$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
